text: okay
hi everyone anthony fantano here the
internet's busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of this new biba
doobie record beetopia this is the
second full-length lp from beatrice
christy laos aka bibadoobe who blew up
in 2019 off of some little indie rock
cuts that had a nostalgic flare one of
which was titled i wish i was stephen
malkmas just to kind of give you guys an
idea of the audience and vibe she was
shooting for there her profile grew even
larger as she dropped tracks like care
and worth it and sorry over the course
of the pandemic these tracks featuring
even heavier helpings of that moody 90s
pastiche which is an era of music i'm
intimately familiar with as i grew up
during it and while the attention to
detail was there maybe more than most
acts throwing it back to this era i just
failed to see what biba do be really
brought to it however i was curious to
see if she sparked up something more
exciting or maybe even new on her new
project here and i suppose with this
record we get a little bit of both there
are at least a few tracks that bring
some heavy driving indie alt rock and
noise pop guitars from a bygone era
whether that be don't get the deal which
has huge huge huge death cap for cutie
vibes coming off of it especially on the
vocals there's 1036 which is one of the
big singles off this project which yes
does have some enjoyably beefy but sweet
riffs though i do think the vocals get
lost in the haze a bit and there's also
talk which is an attempt at a punchier
alt rock track with blown out bass fry
drums for sure the melodies are there
even if the vocals do come off a bit too
listless at least the production has
some damn texture to it but beatrice's
vocals even fold under the thick layers
of strings in the second half of the
track love song truth be told on this lp
she's still far from the strongest front
woman but there are moments on this
thing that feel quite billy eilish in
that we're not hearing the strongest
singer out there but the vibe and
instrumentation complements her very shy
and indirect approach which is
ultimately what's important whether that
be on the song sunny day which is this
little piece of acoustic pop bliss that
sounds like a summery radio jam from the
90s there's a funky looped beat and
relaxed vocal harmonies that match
perfectly it's a great balance of new
and nostalgic and shows bibadoob's knack
for idyllic beauty there's also see you
soon whose stuttering and glitchy beats
pair beautifully with the progressively
thick instrumentation which gets
dreamier and smoother with each passing
moment beatrice's vocal harmonies on top
calling out into a beautiful oblivion
there's ripples which is a
heart-wrenching acoustic cut paired with
some wonderful string work easily one of
the most stunning songs on the entire
record even though it is very soft in
its approach and the perfect pair
switches things up wonderfully in a
little bit of a bossa nova direction
sure the chord progression may not
exactly be revolutionary but the strings
and guitars are elegant as hell and
beatrice's whisper quiet croons strike
this a very sweet and melancholy balance
perfectly there are some spots on this
lp though where the lack of novel
composition ideas leads these songs down
a bland rabbit hole like the closing
track which doesn't have much to offer
outside of being excruciatingly quaint
with uh some weird lines here and there
like when the lights go down don't say i
didn't warn you i don't think that's
legal in the state of cal of california
one more bar that stuck out in an odd
way is on the track fairy song which i
get the point it is a track about
positive affirmations and being willing
to pick yourself up in the midst of
hardship getting out there doing the
damn thing engaging in self-care though
this one line i know you're sad cause
someone died but i'm not gonna sit
inside and do nothing which is a refrain
she really hits on and uh i mean
uh admitted workaholic here okay but
like if if there's any reason to like
pump the brakes it's because some
someone died plus i suppose the sloshy
noise pop instrumentation on the bridge
doesn't really fit with the vibe of the
rest of the track either however there
are some changes of pace in the track
list i thought were pretty novel and
interesting tinkerbell is overrated for
example switches things up with this
bustling indietronic beat as well as
some sweet guest vocals from the one and
only pink panther s which all kind of
blends together especially with the mix
being as compressed and as
dense as it is on the back end there's
also the refreshing pictures of us that
sees beatrice singing over what seems
like some really angular midwestern emo
guitars pretty cool to see the 1975's
matt healy with a co-writing credit on
this one too there's a lot of touching
lyrics on this track and easily one of
the strongest and most mature melodies
on the entire lp as well she reminded me
that god starts with the capital i think
the group vocal approach on this track
works really well too the only issue
that i have with it is that it reaches
this crescendo point super early so it
just kind of builds up very fast and
once it's there it really has nowhere
else to go but with all that being said
uh impressed with the majority of the
tracks on this record really a pretty
clear improvement in terms of
personality song writing style uh from
the debut and i'm actually pretty
interested to see where biba do be goes
from here now that we are not kind of
using that whole 90s nostalgia thing as
just a crutch as now we're engaging with
some better lyricism some versatility
some higher quality production songs
that feel like they have more going for
them other than a connection to the past
so there you go enjoying this one a bit
and certainly encourage you guys to as
well feeling a strong six to a light
seven on this one tran position have you
given this album a listen did you love
it did you hate it what would you rate
it you're the best you're the best what
